Application of ComBat-seq on simulated dataset

library size

Yuqing Zhang

September 25, 2018

Design of the study

We simulated a (2000 gene \(\times\) 20 sample) count matrix from negative binomial distributions. The dataset contains 2 batches, with 10 samples in each batch, and biological effect - a 2-fold change between 2 condition groups.

Simulate dataset

Batch effect in this dataset is in the form of library size change - genes in Batch A are all higher in mean compared to Batch B. We show hiearachical clustering of samples in the dataset based on the unadjusted counts. Samples are clearly clustered by batch - they cluster first by batch (text label), then by biological condition (color). Library sizes and dispersions are different across the two batches.

Distribution of counts in samples

Batch effect in the dataset

Apply ComBat-seq

Adjustment output

We apply ComBat-seq to the above simulated dataset. Some intermediate results of ComBat-seq are printed out to help us better understand how this function works. Running time of ComBat-seq is also recorded.

adj_counts <- ComBat_seq(counts=counts, batch=batch, group=group)

Visualize adjusted data

Similar as above, we visualize the adjusted counts in each sample (first tab), and the average adjusted counts from each gene group (second tab). Also, in the third tab, we can see that after the ComBat-seq adjustment, samples are no longer clustered by batch - rather, they cluster by biological condition as desired.
